title: Easy to use, great for beginners!
review_text: I like the sleek professional look and the quality of this Onn. USB Microphone made for recording vlogs and podcasts, gaming, video calls and more. It‚Äôs easy to set up and use, no need to mess with difficult lengthy installation processes but a quick and straightforward plug and play feature, simply connect the usb cable to your computer and you‚Äôre all set and ready to start. The sound quality is surprisingly good and very clear. I like the 6 feet long cable and easy access volume and mute controls located directly and conveniently at the front of the device. The microphone is also light and portable. The attached desk stand has a swivel feature to easily adjust it to the angle needed. On the backside you find a 1/4‚Äù mic stand thread, a USB-C to usb power port, a headphone jack, as well as the choice of the microphone pickup pattern that lets you choose between omnidirectional or cardioid patterns. I would definitely recommend this recording microphone!

I was broadcasting from home while recovering from illness when my pro gear went bad. This was a quick affordable fix that I could have delivered to my home within hours. It was easy to set up, plug-in-play, and after some minor volume adjustments worked well enough to get me through a few days.

title: Good microphone for the price
review_text: Surprisingly good, cheap desktop microphone. It may not be the greatest microphone ever, but it's definitely good for the price and includes a bevy of features including the ability to mount it, manual gain control, and an audio output device for headphones.

title: versatile and easy-to-use microphone for all use
review_text: We have several other products by this manufacturer and have always been happy with their products. So this microphone is no exception. It is an excellent choice for anyone who wants to record high-quality audio with a versatile and easy-to-use microphone. This microphone has two recording patterns - cardioid and omnidirectional - which makes it ideal for a wide range of recording scenarios. The cardioid recording pattern is perfect for recording sound from a single source, such as a person speaking directly into the microphone. On several runs it perfectly picks up sound from the front of the microphone and rejects sound from the sides and rear, which helps to reduce background noise and improve the clarity of the recorded audio. Excellent for anyone dabbling into podcasting etc. The omnidirectional recording pattern, on the other hand, is ideal for recording sound from multiple sources or for capturing ambient sound. It picks up sound from all directions, which makes it perfect for recording group conversations, musical performances, or environmental sounds. One of the best things about this microphone is pretty easy and straight forward to use. It connects to your laptop via a USB cable and requires no additional drivers or software. Simply plug it in, select the recording pattern you want to use, and start recording. We have not used it with any other devices such as tablets or if it integrates with a phone as seamlessly as with our laptop. But given how nicely it has been made, we imagine it would be a simple process there, too. In terms of sound quality, this microphone delivers excellent results. Perfect for our house needs recording kids videos and all. It seems to be able to handle professional grade recording just fine as well. Pretty decent signal-to-noise ratio, which helps to reduce background noise and improve the clarity of the recorded audio. So, overall, we would highly recommend this microphone to anyone who needs a versatile and easy-to-use recoding device for high-quality audio. Whether you're a podcaster, musician, video creator, or simply use it for family needs (as we do) this microphone is sure to deliver excellent results.

title: Better than you probably expected
review_text: This little microphone is pretty impressive. Cardioid and omnidirectional mode options provide great sound options for podcasts or general voice recording. It's heavier than it looks and even though it's plastic, it doesn't feel or look like a budget friendly microphone. I wanted to try it out and expected to go through some song and dance click fest with warnings and software download prompts, but I got none of that with this on an iMac. On a side note, you may or may not have to set your audio input in the settings if you want to keep it attached and set as default. The USB to USB-C cord is plenty long and feels very durable. On the back of the microphone you have options. You can attach headphones using standard 3.5 mm jack. There's also the option to switch between cardioid or omnidirectional audio. Cardioid mode picks up sounds that are coming from a more precise direction (straight ahead) and omnidirectional picks up all sounds from all directions. There's also an option to attach the microphone to a tripod or hang it to prevent tipping or knocking it over if it's on a desk or table. The button on the front has two colors to let you know when it's muted or actively recording. Blue is recording, red is muted. This is useful in two ways. You can be assured you're not getting any unwanted sounds and also allows for another person to use their own microphone without anyone shifting places or weird scratching sounds while adjusting or moving the microphone. I have thought about doing a podcast in the past and now I know that if I decide to follow through with it, I have the most important piece of equipment in order to do it! Very cool little mic!

One of my favorite features is how easy it is to switch between Bluetooth devices. Whether I'm jumping from my PS5 to my phone or even my iPad, the transition is smooth and hassle-free. It's super convenient and makes the headset feel really versatile. The comfort level is also great ‚Äì lightweight with cushy ear cups that hold up well during long sessions. The only small downside is the mic. It works, but sometimes it doesn't pick up my voice very clearly unless I adjust the boom or speak a little louder. title: Issues with the flip down to unmute mic function
review_text: I would've rated this 5 stars but I have a few concerns/issues regarding this headset and I'm hoping the manufacturer/merchant sees this review and offers help. My first concern is that there were no written instructions or any kind of paperwork/manual in the box; it just contained the headset with the headband, USB receiver and the charging cord, no user documentation as it states on the box. My second concern is that when I am using the headset for work (windows 11 PC) it works great for the most part but my mic is muted even though it is flipped down. Now this is an intermittent issue but a critical issue as I am an inbound call center rep and the issue has occurred at the beginning of receiving a call. I use it with the avaya software as well as Microsoft teams, my mic gets muted when flipped down regardless of the software I'm using at the time. The only ‚Äúfix‚Äù I have found is to flip the mic back up, wait a second and then flip it back down and it'll then unmute. Other than these 2 concerns, the headset is super comfortable - I wear glasses and rarely feel discomfort, it has great audio quality and noise cancellation for both the mic and earpieces. I really like this headset, I can see myself using it for a long time; I just need to find a way to fix the mic muting issue!

title: So far the best gaming headset I have right now!
review_text: I'll try something new with my review format and try to "categorize" things to make this more readable. Audio: The audio is good for a "gaming headset". I say this because headphones made by gaming companies don't offer superior audio compared to headsets made by actual audio companies. But the audio in these are great. Good enough bass, EQ, volume, etc. Again, nothing groundbreaking, but unless you're downgrading from an expensive set, you should be satisfied with the sound quality of these. Controls: The controls are great and straightforward. You have a volume dial on the side and an adjustable microphone. The volume dial is great in that it changes the volume on the device you're connected to, not the volume of the headset itself. This means you don't have two different volumes on both the device and the headphones, you just have one single volume. This is great for convenience, as it means no more fiddling with my Windows volume and headphones volume, it's all set to just one single volume. Build quality: In order to achieve its lightweightness, it had to use materials that are also light as well. This means it will feel "cheap", like a "toy". But it's because of the light plastic and build design. So I can get why people may see it this way, but it personally feels just fine to me. It feels sturdy enough that I don't mind it. And when it comes to it, you really have only two options: Lighter headset, but less premium feel, or heavier headset, but more premium feel. In this case, I prefer a headset that doesn't weigh much, so I'm willing to accept the build quality. The straps and ear cushions feel great as well, and are quite soft without being too soft or too firm. Microphone: The microphone has a great feature where if you put it up, it auto disables itself, and vice versa. The quality is... Not great. If you want professional quality and sound, get an actual standalone mic. Most headset mics, regardless of company, will sound subpar in comparison. But if you don't mind that, then this will suffice. The communication is clear enough in my opinion, and teammates will be able to easily hear you without too much noise or diminished quality. Wireless aspect: It uses a USB. This is an upside and a downside. The upside: You get way less latency. The downside: You don't get Bluetooth. So if your desired device won't take USB, then you basically can't use these with them. Battery life: Lasts me a good amount of time. I can go days without charging it, and I use it a lot daily for videos, music, etc. at around 75% volume. It also has a battery saving feature where it can auto shutoff when it detects it's not in use, which is pretty neat. Overall: Great if you want a light, wireless headset from a reputable brand and don't mind any of the minor downsides that come with it. I recommend purchasing if it's in your budget and you are interested at this point.

title: Unbelievably Good Quality for this Price.
review_text: i bought these headphones on a whim to have some backup headphones for my computer, I mean, ofr this price, hiw could I turn it down? I was SHOCKED at how good of quality these were. I handed them to my younger (adult) brother who is, like me, pretty technically savvy and appreciative of good pairs of headphones. We already have a range of high-quality headphones from Sennheiser, Sony and Skullcandy (their Bluetooth Crushers are amazing for bassheads btw). Anyway, I had him try these headphones on and check out the quality and tell me what he thinks I paid for them. He guessed $120! I personally think that's high, but these are seriously worth at least $50, and if someone had done the same thing with me, I probably would have guessed the retail cost being around $70-80. I just HAD to buy a second pair right away! The cushions are good quality and comfortable, the plastic does NOT feel cheap or fragile, and the headset is very decently sized! My brother and I both have large heads and these fit very comfortably. The headband has metal reinforcement and is very well cushioned. The mic cable is metal and although very easily manipulable, holds its position solidly without fail. The long cable for the connections is hugh quality cloth and all of the connections are very well done so I don't see them getting damaged anytime soon. Even eith all this quality, the headset is still very light and soft on your ears. its clear it was thoughtfully designed for gaming for extended periods. They come with a USB connection, but this seems to only power the LEDs on the headset. The 3.5mm connector the headset has built in is for a mic/headphone combo jack which would work great on a compatible phone or Xbox/Playstation controller, but in case youre using these with a desktop computer that has the mic and headphone jack separated, they come with an adapter for that too. If the manufacturer can make this wired headset for so cheap that it retaisl for $10, they should seriously consider making a Bluetooth version and retailing jt for $15-$20. It would knock out any and all competition in that category at that price point. If you don't mind wired headphones, BUY THESE! You wont regret it!

If I let the cell phone deplete close to zero and plug the power bank to both charge and continue to use the phone, then I might get 1.5 charge during one day. In this case current drawn is 1.8A. Overall, this portable charger is an excellent investment for anyone who needs a dependable and powerful power bank. It's affordable, versatile, and incredibly practical. Highly recommend!

title: Not worth the discount
review_text: This monitor appears nice on the outside, as it is asthetically pleasing, however, once you get on the inside, nothing but disappointment lurks. This is one of those times where the old saying "you get what you pay for" comes into play. There is one, and only one, button on this whole screen and it is a toggle like a joystick that you would find on a game controller. Using this toggle is clunky and awkward, especially with your arm around the screen. Toggling through available selections and selecting something to change is a nightmare all in it's own. This wouldn't be such a big deal if I was only using one input but I often switch between the two and the functionality just ins't there. It's stupid, to say the least. My favorite part is that sometimes when switching between inputs, nothing happens, and you have to unplug the cable you're not trying to use. Lucikly my desk is set up in a way that I can get to the back of it easily, but I shouldn't have to. Aside from input control, the on screen text leaves something to be disired - the font looks...pixelated? I don't know how to explain it other than to say it is NOT clear. If it wasn't for the size of the screen, I would have trouble reading. I have not used this monitor for gaming, so I can't speak to that, but I have used it for streaming which is just o.k. The blacks aren't very deep and the colors are so so. I am using this as a second monitor to a Dell laptop and the Dell is crystal clear for comparison. Overall, this just wasn't a good purchase, and you can order the same monitor from Temu, if that tells you anything.

title: On The Go Gaming
review_text: I first bought this Acer portable monitor for myself, and after seeing how much it improved my workflow, I immediately purchased a second one as a gift for a friend. The display is sharp, bright, and vibrant‚Äîperfect for both work and entertainment. It's lightweight, slim, and slips easily into a laptop bag, making it ideal for travel or working remotely. Setup couldn't be easier: just plug it in and you're ready to go. For me, it's been a total game-changer. Having a second screen on the go makes multitasking, presenting, and organizing so much smoother. My friend has been just as impressed with theirs, and it's already made a big difference in their day-to-day tasks. The build feels sturdy yet sleek, and Acer clearly prioritized both portability and performance. Honestly, I wouldn't hesitate to recommend this monitor to anyone who needs more screen space without being tied to a desk.

title: Nice product
review_text: Great screen if you are looking for something portable, like working out of the office. The case makes it very handy to carry and store. * You have to increase the brightness manually (just the first time), is set to the minimum by default. Don't expect as much brightness as a full size monitor, you won't get it but it's the expected since it does not require a power supply. Also wouldn't pay full price for it, get it on a discount.

title: great price and good quality screen
review_text: I had 8 hour meetings for 6 weeks going over new software, and having only my laptop screen wasn't going to cut it. This screen was a life saver and allowed me to have screens to reference material on. The screen is light but sturdy and fits into my laptop backpack with ease.

title: Light, Versatile, and Samsung DeX Ready
review_text: I use this portable monitor with Samsung DeX, and it works flawlessly. The charging passthrough keeps my phone powered the entire time, which is a huge plus. I also place it right on my piano stand to display sheet music, including interactive apps. I use this for teaching music as well as for my medical work, and it's been incredibly convenient, very light, and easy to carry in your backpack or laptop bag. I also use it with the GeForce Now cloud gaming service, and it delivers a smooth, responsive experience. With a Windows laptop, it works just as well, making it a great all-around second screen. The built-in speakers are pretty bad, but that's not what this monitor is for. The IPS display is bright, sharp, and has great viewing angles, making it perfect for small presentations or sharing content. The only thing I would suggest is for the screen cover protector to have some sort of latch or magnet to keep the sleeve closed snugly. If you need a lightweight, portable second screen that just works, this is an excellent choice.

title: Could've been good
review_text: First off, I ordered the onn. brand and this was substituted because it was out of stock. I needed something immediately so just had to go with it. Surprisingly the .onn brand has basically the same specs, some areas even better than this one, and it's cheaper, but I didn't get to try it out. CONS: 1. The tilt of the screen. There are only two tilt options and both of them are too tilted IMO. I don't want my computer screen to be leaned back, I want it upright in front of me. 2. The cover isn't magenetic. It flaps around and doesn't stay on the front of the screen. It is nice that it's attached permanently at the back so it doesn't come off completely, but I wish it was magnetic to keep the screen protected. PROS: 1. It was on sale for $88 so that's a pretty good deal. 2. You can use a single USB-C to for power and display on your laptop. I had another portable monitor with the same ports as this one, BUT I had to use the USB-C for power and a mini-HDMI for display. It's nice to only need one connection. Ultimately, this worked for me needing something quick and it would've been fine, but the tilt is a deal breaker for me.

title: Dual-screen experience on the go
review_text: I recently purchased the Acer portable screen to use as a second monitor while traveling, and overall, it has been a mixed experience. Pros: - The screen has a sleek and modern design, making it a nice addition to my workspace. - Picture quality is impressive, with clear and vibrant visuals. - It comes with three cables for connectivity: Mini HDMI to HDMI, USB-C to USB-A, and USB-C to USB-C, which is great for versatility. Cons: - Unfortunately, I couldn't get the Mini HDMI to HDMI or USB-C to USB-A cables to work with my laptop. I tried both through my Thunderbolt dock and a direct connection, but neither worked. - The only cable that successfully connected the screen to my laptop was the USB-C to USB-C cable. The same issue occurred when I tested it with my work laptop. While the screen itself is great in terms of design and display quality, the connectivity issues were disappointing even after updating the screen driver. If your laptop supports USB-C, this could be a great travel companion. However, if you rely on Mini HDMI or USB-C to USB-A, you may run into problems.

title: Works well enough

review_text: The Monitor is powered by USB connection I am using the Mini HDMI to HDMI cable, and USB A TO USB C to power. The color and resolution was more than I expected. It provides a excellent 1080p resolution. The price is very competitive with other retailers. I ordered online and had them bring monitor out to my car. I didn't even know they were carried in my store until I looked online. I would buy this again.

title: SCAM! They sent a refurbished monitor!
review_text: Bait and Switch! I purchased what was advertised as a new monitor from Wal Mart. What I received was a refurbished monitor from "East Coast Entities". It even has a sticker that says that it is refurbished; it came without any instructions or warranty information; the cord was wrapped up with a rubber band- none of this was in plastic as all new hardware comes in. This is clearly a used/returned/repaired product. I emailed the seller. Their reply: "Hi, thank you for your message. This item is 100% brand new and unused in the package. We wanted to let you know that only the standard 30-day warranty is applicable for purchases made through Walmart". (Acer's website states that their products have a one year warranty so this seller is simply stating Walmart's return policy). This is a BAIT AND SWITCH SCAM! I will be returning this to Walmart today.

title: Was looking for Old Faithful and got A LOT MORE!!
review_text: I was using an older version of this phone for a couple years with no complaints mostly (until near the end as to be expected) but also with no real raves either. Anyway, I decided to upgrade to THIS, the most recent iteration, as I figured I'd be somewhat familiarized with a new version of the phone I've been using for a couple years rather than jumping into something totally foreign and new. That was a smart choice, and the basic Motorola format, style, features, etc. all translated fairly easily, but I have to say that THIS 2025 model really is exceptional. It looks and feels modern, current, new. It's extremely fast, loaded with great features and apps (a handful of unnecessary/unwanted preloaded apps), the camera is fantastic, tons of storage and a mind boggling amount of storage can be added. Overall, I am very happy with this phone. Enamored enough, in fact, that I eagerly explore every feature and look forward to discovering more. I don't think I've ever had a phone that I was THIS much into right out the gate, and that really says a lot. Excellent!!

title: Great phone, Great price.
review_text: Phone works great. It is basic, but everything works. I am a senior citizen who uses the phone for texting, calling, checking my mail, paying bills. Works well for those things. I don't need and can't afford the newest iPhone or Galaxy. I am very satisfied with the C110.

title: Not Bad For An Entry Level Phone
review_text: Overall, it is a decent phone for an entry level budget phone. Some pros and cons about the phone: Pros 1. I like the size and weight of the phone. Yes, it is made of plastic and not feeling premium. But the biggest advantage is that it is light. I don't feel tired of holding the phone for a long period of time. I also like the aspect ratio of the phone. It is not too tall nor wide. Yes it has side screen bezel, but that doesn't bother me too much. I think the size is about right. 2. It's an android without too much add-ons. Pretty close to the original stock android. 3. It has a headphone jack! 4. As long as not running intensive apps, phone temperature is not bad. Cons: 1. It's a budget phone. Can't expect too much performance. Basical tasks such as web browsing, youtubing and messaging via text app will get the jobs done. But any heavy intensive apps will slow down the phone quite a bit and it just lag. 2. The speaker is on the back of the phone and if it is covered up with finger, no sound. So if you lay it down on a flat surface (without a case), you basically can't hear much. With a case, the phone is lifted up a little and the sound is not that bad. 3. Have a review unit and the phone is locked with a specific carrier, can't really test out call quality. During the initial set up. some random apps just keep installing. But after initial setup, no more. So so: 1. The camera is so so. Again, can't expect too much from an entry level phone. It takes pictures, but can't compare the quality to a premium phone. 2. The battery is okay. I think as long as you don't do too much heavy liftings, the battery can last. Standby overnight battery drain is not bad. Things I wish this phone has: 1. In the gesture setting, I wish it has the function to turn on display when the phone is lifted or double tap to awake. Without the function, the only way to wake up the phone is by pressing power button. 2. I wish they change the position of power and volume buttons. Currently, volume buttons are located on the top and power is below it. It takes some time to get used to. Overall, if you are looking for a budget entry level phone. I think it gets job done. Just don't expect too much performance. It is good for basic tasking.

title: Perfect weight and ease-use combo!
review_text: The C110 combines the physical features of Samsung Galaxy and Iphones, -square-straight all the way around but on the screen edge. But unlike those two, the C110 is light and slightly slimmer, which makes handle and use easier. The back is uniquely Nokia, -scratch-resistant texture and the good-idea speaker slit on the lower-left corner for better output and reception. It's 9/10 user-friendly, providing logical positioning of the home, back and stop buttons, -much better than the Iphone, Samsung and Google Pixel (my current favorite), Start-up had no issues and copying everything from my current had zero glitches. It has only one camera but pixel at 13megap is more than enough that an average person ever uses but the image, though good, is not impressive. The magnification range adjuster comes up when the image is zoomed, and is a smoother option than the tap-choose option on other phones. Video sound is crisp but faint. Sound recording needs to be improved to allow volume increase after recording. Nevertheless, it has enough user-adjustable features and enough options for quick editing and enhancement, Overall, the C110 is a very good phone to have, but needs a big only-on-Nokia identifiable feature, which I was expecting but did not see or feel.
